utherland, Scotland":"Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom","Gigha, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Gigha, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom","England":"England","Strathnaver, Scotland":"Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom","Caithness, Scotland":"Caithness, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacKay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   McKay  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McKay","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aoidh</b> ‘son of <i>Aodh</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘fire’. Etymologically, this is the same name as   McKee  ,   McGee  ,   McCoy  , and   McHugh  .","History: This is the surname of several Irish and Scottish families, including Clan Mackay, a Highland clan traditionally associated with Sutherland in the far northwest of Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Iye","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["pet form of   Isaac .  It was made famous in the 20th century as the nickname of the American general and president  Dwight D. Eisenhower  (  1890–1969 ), although in this case, of course, it was based on his surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Isaac","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the son of Abraham, who was nearly sacrificed by his father according to a command of God which was changed at the last moment. A ram, caught in a nearby thicket, was sacrificed instead (Genesis 22:1–13). Isaac lived on to marry Rebecca and become the father of Esau and Jacob. The derivation of the name is not certain; it has traditionally been connected with the Hebrew verb meaning ‘to laugh’. It was borne by both Christians and Jews in the Middle Ages and was taken up by the Puritans in the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Mor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name from <i>mór</i> ‘large, great’. This was the commonest of all girls’ names in late medieval Ireland, and has continued in use in both Ireland and Scotland to the present day."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Iye Mor MacKay - Second Lord of Strathnaver was born in 1235, in Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Iye Aoidh MacEth, was 27 and his mother, Agnes Rochedale, was 25. He married Euphemia de Baltrodin before 1260, in Caithness, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1325, in Strath, Inverness-shire, Scotland, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1235–1325":"1235–1325","1237–Female":"1237–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1265–1329":"1265–1329","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1208–1268":"1208–1268","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","before 1235":"enne 1235","1330":"1330","1260":"1260","1325":"1325","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","before 1260":"enne 1260","1208":"1208","1329":"1329","Strathnaver, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Strath, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Strathnaver, Sutherland, Scotland":"Sutherland, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Gigha, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Gigha, Argyll and Bute, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Strathnaver, Scotland":"Sutherland, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Caithness, Scotland":"Caithness, Scotland"},"fi":{"1235–1325":"1235–1325","1237–Female":"1237–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1265–1329":"1265–1329","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1208–1268":"1208–1268","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","before 1235":"ennen vuotta 1235","1330":"1330","1260":"1260","1325":"1325","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","before 1260":"ennen vuotta 1260","1208":"1208","1329":"1329","Strathnaver, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Strath, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Strathnaver, Sutherland, Scotland":"Sutherland, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gigha, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom